DA&#8217;s Mmusi Maimane laid the charge at Johannesburg's Rosebank police station. JOHANNESBURG - The Democratic Alliance (DA) says it s going to monitor the police and the National Prosecuting Authority (NPA) after it laid a criminal charge against President Jacob Zuma on Tuesday, accusing him of helping people gain from corruption in government. The party's leader Mmusi Maimane laid the charge at Johannesburg's Rosebank police station, based on the information in Advocate Thuli Madonsela's S[tate of Capture report](http://ewn.co.za/Topic/State-Capture). The report outlined evidence that President Zuma had broken the law by refusing to act on claims that the Gupta family were offering people Cabinet positions.We will make sure Zuma &amp; all those who aid &amp; abet him, are held accountable for their abuse of power to make themselves rich - @MmusiMaimaneDA spokesperson Mabine Seabe says this report shows President Zuma does have a case to answer. As an outcome of having read the state capture report, it s clear that there s a case that needs to be answered for by Zuma and his cabal of criminals. But cases like these are usually handled by the Hawks unit.The head of the Hawks Mthandazo Ntlemeza was appointed to the post by Police Minister Nkosinathi Nhleko after a judge had found he d lied under oath._Read Mmusi Maimane s affidavit here.(Edited by Zamangwane Shange)